## Pillar 4: Security, Compliance & Privacy

### Grade: B+

### ✅ What's Working Well
- **`/api/subscribe` route** correctly hides `GOOGLE_SCRIPT_URL` server-side. The client never sees it. ✅
- **Rate limiting** is implemented (5 req/min/IP). ✅
- **Email validation** is present (basic `includes('@')` check). ✅
- **`apps/web/.env.local`** correctly uses `GOOGLE_SHEETS_API_URL` (no `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix) for the Ventures fetch. ✅

### Finding: Root `.env.local` Exposes Google Script URL
> [!CAUTION]
> The **root** `.env.local` still contains:
> ```
> NEXT_PUBLIC_GOOGLE_SHEETS_API_URL="https://script.google.com/macros/s/AKfycb.../exec"
> ```
> While Next.js in the workspace reads from `apps/web/.env.local`, if this root file is ever committed to Git or referenced by a CI/CD pipeline, the `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix **exposes the URL to the client bundle**. The root `.env.local` must be **deleted**.

### Finding: Rate Limiting is Ephemeral
> [!WARNING]
> The in-memory `Map` for rate limiting **resets on every serverless function cold start**. On Vercel, this means:
> - Every new invocation gets a fresh Map.
> - An attacker can simply wait ~5 minutes for a cold start to bypass limits.
>
> **Recommendation:** For production, use Vercel's `@vercel/kv` (Redis) or Upstash for persistent rate limiting. The current implementation is a reasonable MVP placeholder but should be documented as such.

### Finding: Email Validation is Insufficient
```typescript
if (!email || !email.includes('@'))
```
This passes `@`, `a@`, and `evil<script>@x.com`. At minimum, use a regex like `/^[^\s@]+@[^\s@]+\.[^\s@]+$/` to validate structure. Better yet, use a library like `zod` for schema validation.

### Finding: No CORS Headers on API Route
The `/api/subscribe` route doesn't set CORS headers. While Next.js API routes default to same-origin, explicitly setting `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` and `Access-Control-Allow-Methods` hardens the endpoint against abuse from third-party sites.

### Finding: Google Analytics Without Cookie Consent
> [!IMPORTANT]
> Your Privacy Policy (Section 6) states: *"We use minimal cookies necessary for the core functionality."* However, Google Analytics (`gtag.js`) sets tracking cookies (`_ga`, `_gid`) **automatically on page load** without user consent. Under NDPR and GDPR:
> - Analytics cookies are **not "necessary"** — they require opt-in consent.
> - You need a **cookie consent banner** or must switch to a cookieless analytics solution (e.g., Plausible, Umami, or `gtag` in cookieless mode).
>
> **Risk Level:** Moderate. NDPR enforcement is currently limited, but GDPR applies to any EU visitor to your site.

### Finding: Server Logs Contain PII
```typescript
console.log(`[PIS Labs System] New ecosystem adoption: ${email} from IP: ${ip}`);
```
Logging raw email + IP constitutes PII processing under NDPR/GDPR. If using Vercel's log retention, this data persists in their infrastructure. Mask the email (e.g., `p***@gmail.com`) or remove the log in production.

